title: The Face of Another
author: Abe, Kōbō
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: A man's face is destroyed in an accident so he creates a mask, and slowly the mask seems to take on a life of its own. There are many intriguing ideasA man's face is destroyed in an accident so he creates a mask, and slowly the mask seems to take on a life of its own. There are many intriguing ideas in this book--don't we all wear a mask? To use the language of Lacan, we navigate the symbolic world, adopting voluntarily or involutarily a symbolic form--a female, for instance, with all the accessories and assumptions. And then there is the experience that doesn't fit the symbolic. This is one thing the narrator discovers as he tries to find a way to belong in the world again. I love interior writing but there was far too much of it in this book for me. Things would almost happen, then the mind would intervene and the action would stop. Still, it brought awareness of the role of the face. ...more

review: Yann Martel succeeds because so much of this book is unexpected. The ground rules are established early with Henry (there are two Henrys in this book)Yann Martel succeeds because so much of this book is unexpected. The ground rules are established early with Henry (there are two Henrys in this book) failing to sell his second novel. He wants to write a flip book--one part fiction, one part essay about the Holocaust. His editor, along with a bookseller and a couple others, summarily shoot it down. "That terrifying event was overwhelmingly represented by a single school: historical realism. The story, always the same story, was always framed by the same dates, set in the same places, featuring the same cast of characters." (p.12)Henry encounters a taxidermist who is writing a play-- a story about a donkey and a howler monkey--named Beatrice and Virgil. Soon, Henry is intimately involved with the taxidermist (also named Henry) and the initial set-up of the book is echoed in the play and his encounter with the taxidermist. I don't want to give too much away. But in the end, Martel wonderfully succeeds in using the imaginative space (fiction) to write about the Holocaust. ...more
